Class Octuple<A,B,C,D,E,F,G,H>

    H - the type of the eighth element of the octuple
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Tuple

    public final class Octuple<A,B,C,D,E,F,G,H>
extends AbstractTuple
    Represents a mathematical ordered octuple of objects. The order in which the objects appear in the octuple is significant: the ordered octuple (a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h) is different from the ordered octuple (b, a, c, d, e, f, g, h) unless a and b are equal.
    Author:
    Andre Santos

      • shiftLeft

        public Octuple<B,C,D,E,F,G,H,A> shiftLeft()
        Returns a new tuple, with the members shifted to the left by one position. This operation has a wrapping behaviour, meaning that the member that would be excluded by the shift instead occupies the new open position. For instance, calling ((1, 2, 3)).shiftLeft() would yield the tuple (2, 3, 1).
        Returns:
        a tuple shifted to the left, wrapping around

      • shiftLeft

        public <V> Octuple<B,C,D,E,F,G,H,V> shiftLeft(V value)
        Returns a new tuple, with the members shifted to the left by one position. The given value occupies the new open position, after shifting the original members. For instance, calling ((1, 2, 3)).shiftLeft(4) would yield the tuple (2, 3, 4).
        Type Parameters:
        V - the type of the new member to be inserted
        Parameters:
        value - the new member to be inserted
        Returns:
        a tuple shifted to the left, with the new member given

      • shiftRight

        public Octuple<H,A,B,C,D,E,F,G> shiftRight()
        Returns a new tuple, with the members shifted to the right by one position. This operation has a wrapping behaviour, meaning that the member that would be excluded by the shift instead occupies the new open position. For instance, calling ((1, 2, 3)).shiftRight() would yield the tuple (3, 1, 2).
        Returns:
        a tuple shifted to the right, wrapping around

      • shiftRight

        public <V> Octuple<V,A,B,C,D,E,F,G> shiftRight(V value)
        Returns a new tuple, with the members shifted to the right by one position. The given value occupies the new open position, after shifting the original members. For instance, calling ((1, 2, 3)).shiftRight(0) would yield the tuple (0, 1, 2).
        Type Parameters:
        V - the type of the new member to be inserted
        Parameters:
        value - the new member to be inserted
        Returns:
        a tuple shifted to the right, with the new member given
